04583nam a22008055i 9780231529174DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2001    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315291747 a10.7312/baue116642doi  a(DE-B1597)458644  a(OCoLC)1029561458  a(OCoLC)51311506  a(OCoLC)979969535  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ1190 .B385 2012 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a305.42a305.42/01a305.42011 aBauer, Nancy, eauthor.10aSimone de Beauvoir, Philosophy, and Feminism /cNancy Bauer. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGender and Culture Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction: Recounting Woman -- tCHAPTER 1. Is Feminist Philosophy a Contradiction in Terms? First Philosophy, The Second Sex, and the Third Wave -- tCHAPTER 2. I Am a Woman, Therefrom I Think: The Second Sex and the Meditations -- tCHAPTER 3. The Truth of Self-Certainty: A Rendering of Hegel's Master-Slave Dialectic -- tCHAPTER 4. The Conditions of Hell: Sartre on Hegel -- tCHAPTER 5. Reading Beauvoir Reading Hegel: Pyrrhus et Cinéas and The Ethics of Ambiguity -- tCHAPTER 6. The Second Sex and the Master-Slave Dialectic -- tCHAPTER 7. The Struggle for Self in The Second Sex -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the introduction to The Second Sex, Simone de Beauvoir notes that "a man never begins by establishing himself as an individual of a certain sex: his being a man poses no problem." Nancy Bauer begins her book by asking: "Then what kind of a problem does being a woman pose?" Bauer's aim is to show that in answering this question The Second Sex dramatizes the extent to which being a woman poses a philosophical problem. This book is a call for philosophers as well as feminists to turn, or return to, The Second Sex. Bauer shows that Beauvoir's magnum opus, written a quarter-century before the development of contemporary feminist philosophy, constitutes a meditation on the relationship between women and philosophy that remains profoundly undervalued. She argues that the extraordinary effect The Second Sex has had on women's lives, then and now, can be traced to Beauvoir's discovery of a new way to philosophize-a way grounded in her identity as a woman. In offering a new interpretation of The Second Sex, Bauer shows how philosophy can be politically productive for women while remaining genuinely philosophical.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aFeminism. 0aFeminist theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/baue11664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231529174.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG